context: Raleigh is home to numerous cultural, educational, and historic sites. The <a0_0><b5_0>Duke<b5_0/><a0_0/> Energy Center for the Performing Arts in Downtown Raleigh features three theater venues and serves as the home for the North Carolina Symphony and the Carolina Ballet. <a4_0><b9_0>Walnut Creek Amphitheatre<b9_0/><a4_0/> is a large music amphitheater located in Southeast Raleigh. Museums in Raleigh include the North Carolina Museum of Art in West Raleigh, as well as the North Carolina Museum of History and North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences located next to each other near the State Capitol in Downtown Raleigh. Several major universities and colleges call Raleigh home, including <a1_0><b6_0>North Carolina State University<b6_0/>,<a1_0/> the largest public university in the state, and <a2_0><b7_0>Shaw<b7_0/><a2_0/> University, the first historically black university in the American South and site of the foundation of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee, an important civil rights organization of the 1960s. One U.S. president, <a3_0><b8_0>Andrew Johnson<b8_0/><a3_0/>, was born in Raleigh.
